%I A395286 #17 May 05 2026 00:16:44
%S A395286 9,15,29,52
%N A395286 Positive integers m such that gcd(m^10 - 1, m! - 1) > 1.
%C A395286 For m = 9, gcd(m^10 - 1, m! - 1) = 121 = 11^2, and this shows that there exist integers m > 1 and k > 1 such that gcd(m^k - 1, m! - 1) is not squarefree.
%C A395286 No additional terms are known for m <= 100000 (it is not known whether the sequence is finite).
%C A395286 No additional terms for m <= 5*10^6. - _Michael S. Branicky_, May 01 2026
%e A395286 15 and 29 are terms since gcd(15^10 - 1, 15! - 1) = gcd(29^10 - 1, 29! - 1) = 31.
%o A395286 (PARI) isok(m) = gcd(m^10 - 1, m! - 1) > 1; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Apr 20 2026
%o A395286 (Python)
%o A395286 import math
%o A395286 def isok(m): return math.gcd(m**10-1, math.factorial(m)-1) > 1  # _Jwalin Bhatt_, Apr 28 2026
%Y A395286 Cf. A033312, A069095.
%K A395286 nonn,hard,more,changed
%O A395286 1,1
%A A395286 _Marco Ripà_, Apr 18 2026
